  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and agreements designed to combat money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - An intergovernmental organization that sets global standards for preventing money laundering\n\n2. United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n\n3. The Palermo Convention, which provides a framework for international cooperation against organized crime\n\n4. Basel Committee's guidelines on banking regulations\n\n5. The International Money Laundering Information Network (IMoLIN)\n\nThese frameworks require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs\n\nMost countries have their own national laws implementing these international standards, with penalties for non-compliance.",
